The Map interface in Java is a key component of the Java Collections Framework. It is designed for storing key-value pairs, where each key is associated with a specific value. In this article, we'll discuss several important methods in the Map interface, their usage, and their functionality.

-> Methods of the Map Interface in Java
  put(K key, V value)
• The put method is used to add a key-value pair to a map. If the key is already present, it replaces the old value with the new one; otherwise, it inserts a new key-value pair.
• It also returns the previous value associated with the key, or null if the key was not present.

import java.util.*;
​
class GfG {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Map<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();
​
        map.put(100, "GfG");
        map.put(200, "Courses");
        map.put(150, "IDE");
​
        System.out.println(map);
    }
}

Output
{100=GfG, 150=IDE, 200=Courses}
Note: HashMap does not maintain any order. The output order may vary each time when we run  the program .

get(Object key)
The get method retrieves the value associated with the specified key. If the key is not present, it returns null.
    String value = map.get(100);
    System.out.println(value); 
Output:
GfG
  If you try to get a value with a key that doesn't exist:
    String value = map.get(999);
    System.out.println(value); 
Output:
null

isEmpty()
The isEmpty method checks if the map contains any key-value pairs. It returns true if the map is empty, and false otherwise.
    boolean isEmpty = map.isEmpty();
    System.out.println(isEmpty);
Output:
false

remove(Object key)
  The remove method removes the key-value pair for the specified key. It returns the value associated with the key, or null if the key does not exist.
String removedValue = map.remove(200);
System.out.println(removedValue); 
System.out.println(map); 
Output:
Courses
{100=GfG, 150=IDE}

containsKey(Object key)
  The containsKey method checks if a given key exists in the map. It returns true if the key is present, otherwise false.
boolean contains = map.containsKey(100);
System.out.println(contains); 
Output:
true

containsValue(Object value)
The containsValue method checks if a given value exists in the map. It returns true if the value is present, otherwise false.
boolean containsValue = map.containsValue("IDE");
System.out.println(containsValue); 
Output:
true

replace(K key, V value)
The replace method replaces the existing value for a given key with a new value. It only works if the key already exists.
map.replace(150, "Java");
System.out.println(map); 
Output:
{100=GfG, 150=Java, 200=Courses}

size()
The size method returns the number of key-value pairs in the map.
int size = map.size();
System.out.println(size); 
Output:
3

keySet()
The keySet method returns a set view of all the keys present in the map.
Set<Integer> keys = map.keySet();
System.out.println(keys);
Output:
[100, 150, 200]

values()
The values method returns a collection view of all the values in the map. Since values can be duplicated, it returns a collection, not a set.
Collection<String> values = map.values();
System.out.println(values);
Output:
[GfG, Java, Courses]

entrySet()
The entrySet method returns a set view of all the key-value mappings in the map. This is useful for traversing through a map and working with both keys and values together.
Set<Map.Entry<Integer, String>> entries = map.entrySet();
for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : entries) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " = " + entry.getValue());
}
Output:
100 = GfG
150 = Java
200 = Courses

getOrDefault(Object key, V defaultValue)
The getOrDefault method returns the value associated with the key if it exists, or a default value if the key is not found.
String defaultValue = map.getOrDefault(300, "Not Found");
System.out.println(defaultValue); 
Output:
Not Found

clear()
The clear method removes all the mappings from the map, making it empty.
map.clear();
System.out.println(map);
Output:
{}
